| {{unicode|''p<U+00E1>ta<U+1E25>''}}
| {{hebrew|{{hbrppe}}<U+05B7>{{hbrtav}}<U+05B7>{{hbrhet}}}}
| rowspan=1 | {{IPA|/a/}}
| a
|  A patach on a letter <U+05D7> at the end of a word is sounded ''before'' the letter, and not after.  Thus, <U+05E0><U+05B9><U+05D7><U+05B7> (Noah) is pronounced /''no-ax''/.  This only occurs at the ends of words and only with patach and <U+05D7>, <U+05E2>, and <U+05D4><U+05BC> (that is, <U+05D4> with a dot (mappiq) in it).  This is sometimes called a ''patach g'nuvah'', or "stolen" patach (more formally, "furtive patach"), since the sound "steals" an imaginary epenthetic consonant to make the extra syllable.
